<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Jim Wright Protests
   Charge as Untrue
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   Your July 16 editorial "The Price of Silence" makes a very
valid point that "the essential cause of the S&amp;L debacle is
in danger of being lost amid the political name-calling."
Unfortunately, you revive and give currency to a grossly
inaccurate bit of name-calling in which I was the unhappy
target.
   You cite a singularly contemptible charge "that Mr. Wright
threatened to expose one S&amp;L regulator as a homosexual and
browbeat others to go easy on Democratic campaign
contributors."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   That charge is untrue. To make a threat of that kind would
be totally alien to my character. I did not do anything of
that sort and I would not. Nobody who knows me well at all
would believe that I had ever been so crude as that.
   My judgment, like that of other mortals, is imperfect. I
have made my share of mistakes, no doubt. But I do not want
that particular bit of calumny left unanswered in the public
record.
   Jim Wright
   Member of Congress, 1953-1989
   Speaker of the House, 1987-1989
   Fort Worth, Texas
</TEXT>
