<HL>
   DeSoto Agrees to Sell
   U.S. Paint Operation
   To Sherwin-Williams
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   DSO SHW
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   DES PLAINES, Ill. -- DeSoto Inc. said it agreed to sell
its domestic consumer paint business to Sherwin-Williams Co.
for about $80 million.
   The Sherwin-Williams pact is the latest in a series of
agreements which, taken together, represent a near-total
liquidation, with proceeds to be distributed to shareholders.
DeSoto, a maker of paints, chemical coatings and detergents,
has since last November been fighting off a hostile
$50-a-share tender offer from Sutton Holding Corp., a New
York investor group.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last week DeSoto announced that it had agreed to sell its
industrial coatings business and its surfactant and
emulsifier lines for about $200 million. The company
disclosed then that it was "very close" to an agreement on
the sale of its paint operation.
   The paint unit's operations have been estimated at more
than $150 million in 1989, but competitive pressures have
generated operating losses in recent quarters.
   As with the earlier unit-sale agreements, the planned sale
of the paint operation is subject to approval by shareholders
and regulators. DeSoto said it will distribute the net
proceeds -- expected to be around $60 million, or about
$14.97 a share -- to shareholders. Combined with the $27.84
the company has said it expects to distribute from proceeds
of the agreements announced earlier, DeSoto holders stand to
receive about $42.81 a share from the agreements so far.
   Still unsold is certain proprietary technology, which is
on the block but not expected to garner a significant price,
and the company's household-detergent business, which had
revenue last year of about $72 million. DeSoto has said it
will "for the present" retain the detergent operation.
   DeSoto undertook the sale of the company's principal lines
after a Delaware court, in the course of the company's legal
dispute with Sutton, ordered it to take steps to maximize
shareholder value.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading, DeSoto
shares closed at $46, up 12.5 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
