<HL>
   Business Brief -- Supercomputing Solutions Inc.:
   Loss Widens in 2nd Quarter
   And Prompts Cost Cutting
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   SUPR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Supercomputing Solutions Inc. said its loss widened to
$1.1 million, or 17 cents a share in the second quarter, and
said it plans to cut its staff by 50% and take other
cost-cutting steps due to "an uncomfortable cash position."
   In the year-earlier period, the San Diego-based maker and
seller of supercomputers and software reported a loss of
$743,836, or 17 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the recent quarter, revenues more than doubled to
$738,723 from $360,752. The gains were due to the company's
completion of a subcontract for the initial phase of the
Direct Solution of Turbulence Program for the Department of
Defense and the completion and sale of the company's first
CAPPS-9064 supercomputer to TRW Inc.
   However, the company said research and development costs
linked to the CAPPS-9064 resulted in significant losses,
leaving the company in an "uncomfortable cash position."
   The company said its cost-saving efforts will include
cutbacks in travel and capital-equipment expenditures as well
as the curtailment of a research grant to Princeton
University.
</TEXT>
