<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   S&amp;L Cleanup Law's Measures Weakened
   By Court Rulings, Relaxed Regulations
   ----
   By Paulette Thomas
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- As political accusations over the
savings-and-loan mess build, the tough measures in last
year's S&amp;L cleanup law intended to ward off a future disaster
are quietly being undermined by court rulings and eased
thrift regulations.
   The S&amp;L cleanup law, passed last August, forced thrifts to
abandon accounting rules that had allowed them to hide losses
for years. The law also wiped out contracts between the
government and buyers of S&amp;Ls in which buyers believed they
had special dispensation to continue using the accounting
rules. But in isolated cases, both are being weakened.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "I think it's significant," says Karen Shaw of the
Institute for Strategy Development, a Washington banking
consultant. "Those are relatively unrelated events decided
for different reasons, but they are happening."
   In return for hitting up taxpayers for $130 billion -- not
including hundreds of billions of dollars more in interest --
the S&amp;L cleanup law racheted up capital standards. The
capital represents the investment that thrift shareholders
have at risk, and it acts as a cushion to protect the
taxpayer-backed deposit insurance fund.
   But already, four federal judges have blocked the Office
of Thrift Supervision from seizing insolvent institutions,
based on contracts that those thrifts had with the federal
government. And recently, the thrift office delayed a
provision of the S&amp;L bailout law that limited a thrift's
exposure to loss from any one borrower. The thrift office
then delayed for review a proposed regulation to increase the
amount of capital to be held for certain loans backed by the
Department of Veterans Affairs.
   The thrift office, which contends that capital standards
haven't been eroded, said it was appealing the four cases. A
spokesman said that the office has prevailed in four suits
filed by other thrifts seeking to block federal takeover.
   "The Office of Thrift Supervision believes that capital is
king," Director Timothy Ryan said yesterday. "We will do
nothing to erode the (cleanup law) capital standards, which
we view as the most important provision of the statute."
   The most recent court ruling was Monday, when federal
Judge Thomas G. Hull in Tennessee issued a permanent
injunction blocking regulators from seizing Franklin Federal
Savings Bank of Morristown, Tenn., with $107 million in
assets.
   The court ruled that the thrift had a solid contract with
the government in which the S&amp;L was permitted to count
certain losses as capital and therefore couldn't be seized as
insolvent.
   Some industry-watchers say the courts are just recognizing
what they have contended for the past year -- that Congress,
in a vengeful mood over the costs of the cleanup, went too
far. They say that the law set standards too high and that
the thrift office is inflexible. The Resolution Trust Corp.,
the new bailout agency, has so many insolvent thrifts to sell
that, to cut its losses, it is trying to find buyers for
failing S&amp;Ls even before they are seized.
   "You can sit in your ivory tower and dictate what should
be true, but when you are out there in the trenches, you have
to recognize reality," says Richard Kneipper, a Dallas thrift
attorney.
   Seven other court cases contesting capital rules are
pending in federal courts across the country, and more are
certain to be filed. Attorneys say that many of the suits are
frivolous but that some thrifts make a compelling case that
they were induced by the government to acquire failing S&amp;Ls,
based on the special capital provisions.
   "The law was passed in a spirit of blunt-edged machismo,"
says Ms. Shaw. "The regulators are now in between a very hard
rock and a very hard place."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900719-0007
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900719-0007.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Gannett, New York Times Net Declined
   In 2nd Quarter, Reflecting Drop in Ads
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   GCI NYTA
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Two major newspaper publishers reported lower
earnings for the second quarter, reflecting a nationwide
slump in advertising so persistent it is now hurting one of
the industry's best performers.
   Gannett Co. and the New York Times Co., publishers of
daily newspapers in major cities as well as smaller markets,
had been expected to report lower earnings. Yet while the
falling ad market has battered the industry for at least a
year, Arlington, Va.-based Gannett's results were especially
noteworthy: It was the first time since going public in 1967
that it reported a quarterly earnings drop from the
comparable period a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Gannett earnings were $105.3 million, or 66 cents per
share, compared with $112.1 million, or 70 cents, a year
earlier. Revenue fell 1% to $893.8 million from $904.2
million.
   Gannett sold a radio station in Seattle, but it
represented only a "minor" gain, the company said.
   Gannett executives blamed "continuing restructuring in the
retail industry and a deteriorating consumer economy" for
stalling the revenue growth. Major department stores, some
hit by bankruptcy reorganizations and consolidations, are
traditionally among Gannett's largest advertisers.
   Troubling for all newspapers is that classified
advertising continues its fall, after years of robust growth
in the 1980s. Gannett said classified volume at most of its
83 daily newspapers declined for cars, real estate and help
wanted.
   At Gannett's flagship, USA Today, the number of ad pages
in the first six months fell 9% to 1,780. Gannett said,
though, that ad rate increases and higher circulation
resulted in a revenue gain of 3% for the first half.
Gannett's outdoor advertising unit, the largest billboard
company in North America, reported an increase in revenue but
the broadcasting division, including radio and TV stations,
reported a decline.
   Peter Appert, analyst for C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell
Inc., called Gannett's drop in revenue troubling. "Earnings
will continue to be under pressure if revenues continue in
this range," he said. "And there's nothing in the next
quarter that says it will turn around."
   For the six months, Gannett said net fell 4% to $180.3
million, or $1.13 a share, from $187.0 million, or $1.16 a
share. Revenue for the first six months dropped 1% to $1.7
billion.
   At the New York Times Co., still reeling from slumping ad
linage at its flagship daily, the earnings drop wasn't as
steep as some analysts had expected.
   The company reported earnings of $26.8 million, or 35
cents a share, compared with $39.2 million, or 50 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenue for the quarter rose to $468.9
million from $460.3 million.
   "We thought they might come in at about 27 cents, so it's
better than we expected," said Jeffrey Russell, an analyst
for Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. "They are holding the
margins as well as they can, considering the poor ad climate
in New York."
   New York Times executives said the earnings drop was
largely a result of lower ad linage at the Times, brought on
by a weak New York area economy. Earnings also suffered from
the acquisition of McCall's magazine, and increased
depreciation and interest expense related to completion of
the Times's color printing plant in Edison, N.J. and a newly
constructed facility for the Gwinnett (Ga.) Daily News.
   About 60% of the loss in ad linage at the Times was in
classified ads for help wanted, real estate and automotive.
   For the six months, net income was $43.4 million, or 57
cents a share, compared with $70.7 million, or 90 cents a
share, last year. Revenue for the period grew by 2% to $900.1
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
