900719-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Corporate Focus:
   Steel Union's Troubles Get Even Worse
   ---
   Convictions of Two Top
   Officials Spark Distrust
   ----
   By Clare Ansberry
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR X
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
</IN>
<LP>
   The United Steelworkers of America knew 1990 would be
tough.
   The union faces contract talks with the industry's most
combative negotiator, USX Corp. At the same time, it must
beef up efforts to find new dues-paying members to replace
thousands laid off in the 1980s.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The year just got tougher. Last week, two high-ranking
union officials were found guilty of conspiracy and
violations of the Taft-Hartley Act. The government said the
union officials, along with USX, which was found guilty of 14
related counts, received secret pension benefits as part of a
conspiracy to win significant concessions in 1983. The
trend-setting pact ultimately resulted in reopening USX's
then-idled Fairfield, Ala., plant.
   Labor experts say the convictions could strain what
already promise to be tense negotiations with the nation's
largest steelmaker. More important, the convictions could
hurt the union's credibility among some rank-and-file
members, still smarting from such concessionary contracts.
   Although both the company and union say they're confident
the convictions will be overturned, the damage is largely
done. Buddy Davis, a union director, says that convictions
make big news, while reversals don't. Moreover, he says,
"even though I'm confident the charges will be dropped,
you'll still have people talking behind their {union
officials'} backs saying, `They got off the hook.' "
   The timing couldn't have been worse. The USW had finally
begun to get back on its feet after a decade marred by
layoffs and divisive elections for top officials. It had
become more militant -- weathering a tough strike against USX
in 1986, its first in 26 years -- and more progressive by
creating employee-owned plants. Furthermore, membership had
stopped its downward spiral in recent years, and last year
the union negotiated rich contracts with four major
steelmakers.
   "In the last five years, we've pulled together and gotten
a lot more unity," says Mr. Davis. "This is the last thing we
need."
   Some rank-and-file members, feeling cheated, have already
sued the union. A group in Birmingham, Ala., seeking wages
and benefits lost in the concessions, claims the union
breached not only its fiduciary duty but its duty of fair
representation. And Larry Regan, president of Local 1014 in
Gary, Ind., plans to file a second suit. He said the
Fairfield pact set a pattern of concessions -- including
reducing work crews to unsafe levels -- for future contracts
at plants around the country. "You had people committing
suicides and being injured because of these concessions," he
says.
   The union already is seeing the impact on its efforts to
gain and retain members. At O'Neal Steel Inc. in Birmingham,
where 250 union members in four plants voted to decertify the
union, the indictments against the union officials became a
campaign issue. "We certainly weren't bashful about
mentioning it," says Raymond Lindsey, O'Neal's vice president
of human resources.
   Andrew Turner, who was the local president until the
decertification, says members were more concerned about job
security than about the indictment. "But this hurt. Some
members said they didn't want a bunch of crooks representing
them," he says.
   The union has warned its organizers that companies would
use the conviction as an anti-union club. "I'm sure this is
going to bite us in some places," says Mr. Davis. Membership
in his own district has dropped to 18,000 from a high of
36,000 a decade ago, and he has fewer staff members trying to
organize a larger number of small plants.
   One point the union is stressing in its defense is that
most companies offer pension benefits to union officials --
which the court has deemed illegal. A Department of Labor
survey found that 62% of U.S. manufacturers provide such
benefits to labor representatives even though they're
employed by unions.
   Carl Frankel, a USW staff attorney, says the convictions
"won't cause us to lose an {organizing} election that
otherwise we'd win. No doubt we'll have to deal with this,
but we've had other challenges, and we'll get through this
one."
   How last week's verdict will play out with USX
negotiations isn't quite clear, but some people say the union
and USX, both fearing any cozy appearance, might be more
hard-nosed than normal.
   The Steelworkers want to pattern contracts after one
signed last year by Bethlehem Steel Corp., the first major
steelmaker to reach an accord. USX has already scoffed at the
pact, calling it "too generous." Moreover, the company is
willing to sell its steel operations at the right price, and
it can threaten during talks to do so to a less
union-friendly company.
   Ben Fischer, director of the Center for Labor Studies at
Carnegie Mellon University, fears that the ruling will ban
nearly all collaborative arrangements, even if they benefit
rank-and-file workers and employers. It could also taint any
concessionary contract, even when it's needed for a company
to survive.
   "The only thing that becomes safe is arms-length
adversarial relationships," he said. "That way, even though
you may destroy the institution, you protect yourselves."
   Labor experts also warn that the convictions could
increase friction between top USW officials and local plant
presidents, making it more difficult for the union to
solidify its negotiating stance against USX. Local leaders
have always wanted more control over individual plant issues,
such as holidays, contracting out and maintenance schedules,
but with the convictions they may feel more justified in
distancing themselves from headquarters.
   "There has always been friction," said economist Don
Barnett. "This just means more mistrust."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900719-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900719-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Republicans Seek Guarantees From Democrats
   On Spending as Part of Deficit-Reduction Plan
   ----
   By David Wessel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- When the subject of the budget process came
up at the deficit talks recently, Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady was out of town, Budget Director Richard Darman came in
late and Rep. Dan Rostenkowski (D., Ill.) slipped out early
to go to a ball game.
   Clearly, "budget process" is a topic that bores even the
most devoted of the budget negotiators. In two months of
talks, they've devoted precisely one day to it.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But don't be fooled. Changing the process is critical to
getting a budget accord because the White House has made it a
top priority. Many congressional Republicans, convinced that
past bipartisan accords have failed to limit spending, agree.
The House Republican Whip, Newt Gingrich of Georgia, told
fellow negotiators the other day that if he had to walk out
of the room uttering the "T-word," they would have to utter
the "C-word" -- control of spending.
   What President Bush and the Republicans are looking for is
some guarantee that any tax increase will go to reduce the
deficit -- not to fuel more spending. That means pushing
Democrats to establish in advance firm spending totals for
defense and domestic programs for the next five years, and
then finding a way to make that promise stick. "Whatever we
come to agreement on would have to be enforceable on a
multi-year basis," says Mr. Darman. "That has never been
possible before."
   In speeches, Mr. Bush has highlighted the need for a
line-item veto -- a change favored by conservatives that
would give the president the power to pluck wasteful
porkbarrel projects out of massive spending bills.
   But the line-item veto isn't considered a realistic
solution. In private, Bush administration officials concede
that Congress isn't about to surrender so much power to the
president. Moreover, it isn't clear that the veto would be
much help in cutting the deficit. "It's symbolic," says
political scientist Thomas Mann of the Brookings Institution,
a Washington think tank. "The president would find it
extraordinarily difficult to do anything with the line-item
veto that would add up to numbers that would make any
difference as far as the deficit is concerned."
   Efforts to change the budget process to enforce a
bipartisan deficit-reduction accord are undeniably arcane.
"The public doesn't understand the process, and you can't
explain it to them," says Sen. Bennett Johnston (D., La.).
But the process can be immensely important. The Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction law has been driving tax and spending
policy for the past five years. And because any change in the
process tends to alter the balance of power in Congress, the
resistance to altering the budget process is substantial.
   Any agreement at the budget talks to raise taxes or save
money on benefit programs like Medicare or Social Security
will be written into law and won't require new enforcement
mechanisms. But the spending levels for the Pentagon and for
domestic programs ranging from space to sewers are less
certain. Those spending levels are set annually and, as a
result, the congressional appropriations committees can
easily undo any agreements made by the summiteers.
   Republicans want guarantees that that won't happen. "I
want assurance that, but for absolutely unexpected events,
the end result is achieved," says Sen. Pete Domenici of New
Mexico, senior Republican on the Senate Budget Committee.
   Participants in the talks say Mr. Darman has proposed
fixing by law five years of spending totals for defense,
overall domestic programs and foreign aid, a step that
basically would prevent any changes to the summit
understandings without the president's consent.
   An alternative plan being circulated by the private
Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget would alter the
Gramm-Rudman law to target automatic spending cuts
specifically at appropriations subcommittees that overspend
their allocations. A subcommittee that overshot its target
one year would be penalized the following year. The
Gramm-Rudman deficit targets would be dropped in favor of the
new spending ceilings.
   Democrats are resistant to all these proposals. "I don't
want to be a party to any mechanism that diminishes the
constitutional authority of Congress to control spending
bills," says Senate Budget Committee Chairman James Sasser
(D., Tenn.). Some Democrats say they might go along with new
parliamentary hurdles for spending bills that exceed
summit-set totals, but the summit isn't likely to resolve the
process issues until after it strikes a compromise on a
package of spending cuts and tax increases.
   Much of the disagreement isn't about how much the
government spends in total, but what the money goes for. The
administration, for instance, wants the summit to set a floor
under defense spending to protect it from attempts to make
deeper cuts in the future. Some Democrats complain that the
world is changing too fast to lock in a five-year commitment
now.
   In the end, though, the issue is one of power rather than
policy. Democratic and Republican members of appropriation
committees cherish their role in divvying up the federal
spending pie. Negotiators from both sides expect Sen. Robert
Byrd (D., W.Va.) and Rep. Jamie Whitten (D., Miss.), chairmen
of the appropriations committees, to be among the last
obstacles to an agreement on writing rules to enforce a
summit agreement.
   Even convening the ad hoc congressional-White House summit
steps on their toes. Indeed, Rep. Whitten occasionally rises
from his chair at the summit talks -- the only participant
who stands to speak -- and protests that the entire
enterprise is improperly encroaching on his turf.
</TEXT>
